{
  "@context": "https://fnsr.example/context.jsonld",
  "@id": "urn:fnsr:run:demo-001",
  "tasks": [
    {
      "@id": "urn:fnsr:task:001-review",
      "agent": "spec-reviewer",
      "status": "done",
      "inputs": {
        "artifact": "GraphWrite Edge Canonical Modeling Specification",
        "version": "v0.4 Engineering-Ready",
        "artifact_path": "project/SPEC.md",
        "focus": "OWL DL conformance, CCO/IAO realist anchoring, and Visual Modeler Profile completeness"
      },
      "outputs": {
        "artifact": "GraphWrite Edge Canonical Modeling Specification",
        "version": "v0.4 Engineering-Ready",
        "artifact_path": "project/SPEC.md",
        "focus": "OWL DL conformance, CCO/IAO realist anchoring, and Visual Modeler Profile completeness",
        "recommendation": "revise",
        "summary": {
          "total_findings": 19,
          "blocking": 5,
          "major": 8,
          "minor": 4,
          "advisory": 2
        },
        "findings": [
          {
            "id": "F1",
            "severity": "blocking",
            "category": "version_coherence",
            "claim": "Version-label incoherence: the document header declares v0.4 Engineering-Ready, but \u00c2\u00a73.1, \u00c2\u00a73.2, \u00c2\u00a721, and \u00c2\u00a722 are still scoped/titled for v0.3. A v0.4 implementer cannot tell which Scope, MVP, or Test Strategy section applies.",
            "evidence": "Header (line 4): 'Specification version: v0.4 Engineering-Ready'. \u00c2\u00a73.1 title (line 176): 'In Scope for v0.3 Engineering Baseline'. \u00c2\u00a73.2 title (line 200): 'Out of Scope for v0.3 MVP'. \u00c2\u00a721 lead (line 1429): 'This section is normative for v0.3 \"engineering-ready\" status.' \u00c2\u00a722 title (line 1483): 'MVP Definition v0.3'. The DoD \u00c2\u00a731 is titled 'for v0.4 Engineering Baseline' but cites these v0.3-scoped sections by name.",
            "impact": "Conformance scope is undefined; downstream FR/NFR coverage cannot be measured."
          },
          {
            "id": "F2",
            "severity": "blocking",
            "category": "validation_taxonomy",
            "claim": "Severity taxonomy is internally contradictory. \u00c2\u00a717.1 declares info findings 'informational only', yet \u00c2\u00a717.4 and \u00c2\u00a710.4 make LEGACY_REALIST_ANCHOR_PLACEHOLDER (severity info) block export. The same condition (placeholder iao:isAbout) is simultaneously an error (MISSING_REALIST_ANCHOR per \u00c2\u00a717.2) and info (LEGACY_REALIST_ANCHOR_PLACEHOLDER per \u00c2\u00a717.4) depending on provenance, with identical blocking semantics.",
            "evidence": "\u00c2\u00a717.1 (line 1238): 'Info findings are informational only.' \u00c2\u00a717.4 (line 1278) LEGACY_REALIST_ANCHOR_PLACEHOLDER row: 'does not block save but does block export.' \u00c2\u00a710.4 (line 900): 'The placeholder does not block save of the migrated file, but it does block export until the user declares a real iao:isAbout.' \u00c2\u00a75.4.1 (line 392): '... emits validation finding MISSING_REALIST_ANCHOR (an error) or LEGACY_REALIST_ANCHOR_PLACEHOLDER (info, after v0.3 migration). The placeholder ... blocks export by default.'",
            "impact": "Downstream tooling cannot decide blocking behavior from severity alone; the three-level severity contract is broken."
          },
          {
            "id": "F3",
            "severity": "blocking",
            "category": "requirements_coverage",
            "claim": "No FR-C identifier exists for the v0.3 \u00e2\u2020\u2019 v0.4 migration mandated by \u00c2\u00a710.4 and DoD \u00c2\u00a731 item 15. FR-C013 covers only v0.2 \u00e2\u2020\u2019 v0.3.",
            "evidence": "\u00c2\u00a718.1 FR-C013 (line 1313): 'Migrate legacy v0.2 documents to v0.3 on load (\u00c2\u00a710.4).' \u00c2\u00a710.4 (lines 889-902) specifies the v0.3 \u00e2\u2020\u2019 v0.4 migration steps (specVersion bump, context expansion, type promotion to ['ecm:Project','iao:OntologyDesignPattern'], iao:isAbout placeholder init, LEGACY_REALIST_ANCHOR_PLACEHOLDER emission, ecm:serializations init). \u00c2\u00a731 DoD #15 (line 1780): 'Legacy v0.2 and v0.3 documents migrate to v0.4 cleanly with a migration report.' No FR-C in \u00c2\u00a718.1 gates this normative behavior with acceptance criteria.",
            "impact": "The v0.3 \u00e2\u2020\u2019 v0.4 migration leg is normatively required but has no acceptance criterion; conformance verification is impossible."
          },
          {
            "id": "F4",
            "severity": "blocking",
            "category": "namespace_authority",
            "claim": "iao:OntologyDesignPattern is minted in the OBO Information Artifact Ontology namespace (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/iao#) without IAO authority. The spec itself admits IAO does not define this class. Every realist-anchoring claim in v0.4 depends on this hijacked IRI.",
            "evidence": "\u00c2\u00a75.2 @context (line 297): '\"iao\": \"http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/iao#\"' \u00e2\u20ac\u201d the canonical OBO IAO namespace. \u00c2\u00a75.2 prose (line 323): 'The iao: prefix is used for the project-introduced term iao:OntologyDesignPattern (see \u00c2\u00a75.14 \u00e2\u20ac\u201d the term is shipped by this spec's TBox; core IAO does not currently define it).' \u00c2\u00a75.14 Notes (line 640): 'iao:OntologyDesignPattern is introduced by this spec. Core IAO does not currently define an Ontology Design Pattern class.' \u00c2\u00a75.14 TBox (line 609-612) and \u00c2\u00a722 MVP step 18 require this term in every semantic export.",
            "impact": "Linked-data consumers dereferencing http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/iao#OntologyDesignPattern will get a 404 or an unrelated IAO term. Realist-anchored claims (NFR-014, DoD \u00c2\u00a731 items 1, 2, 11) rest on a misappropriated IRI. Either mint under ecm: (and bump TBox accordingly) or coordinate authority with IAO before declaring v0.4 engineering-ready."
          },
          {
            "id": "F5",
            "severity": "blocking",
            "category": "determinism",
            "claim": "UUIDv5 namespace UUID is unspecified. \u00c2\u00a79.3 and \u00c2\u00a713.9 require deterministic UUIDv5 'derived from the seed and the operation context', but the RFC-4122 namespace UUID and the canonical name-encoding (which operation-context fields, in what order, encoded how) are not defined. NFR-013 byte-identicality across implementations is therefore unachievable for any project that uses deterministic IRIs.",
            "evidence": "\u00c2\u00a79.3 (line 850): 'UUIDs are replaced with UUIDv5 derived from the seed and the operation context.' \u00c2\u00a713.9 (line 1040): 'In ecm:deterministic mode (\u00c2\u00a79.3), IRI generation uses UUIDv5 derived from the seed and the operation context.' NFR-013 (line 1422): 'Two compliant implementations produce byte-identical canonical and derived artifacts per \u00c2\u00a79.1.' UUIDv5 (RFC 4122 \u00c2\u00a74.3) requires a fixed namespace UUID input; none is given. The seed-to-namespace mapping, the operation-context serialization rules, and the canonical-name byte encoding are absent.",
            "impact": "Conformance NFR-013 is unverifiable in deterministic mode; two implementations will produce different UUIDs from the same seed."
          },
          {
            "id": "F6",
            "severity": "major",
            "category": "architecture_alignment",
            "claim": "SPEC \u00c2\u00a74.1 defines a five-layer system model (Core Computation / State Adapter / Orchestration / Integration / UI Adapter) that is unreconciled with the three-layer model (kernel / composition / adapters) declared in ARCHITECTURE.md \u00c2\u00a74, CLAUDE.md \u00c2\u00a76, and enforced by npm run test:purity. No mapping is provided.",
            "evidence": "SPEC \u00c2\u00a74.1 enumerates 4.1.1 Core Computation, 4.1.2 State Adapter, 4.1.3 Orchestration, 4.1.4 Integration, 4.1.5 UI Adapter (lines 229-260). ARCHITECTURE.md \u00c2\u00a74 (line 37-43): three layers \u00e2\u20ac\u201d Layer 0 Kernel, Layer 1 Composition, Layer 2 Adapters. CLAUDE.md \u00c2\u00a76: 'Layer 0: src/kernel/ ... Layer 1: src/composition/ ... Layer 2: src/adapters/.' CLAUDE.md \u00c2\u00a74: 'Violations are caught by npm run test:purity.'",
            "impact": "Implementers cannot tell whether 'Orchestration' maps to composition or adapters, where 'State Adapter' fits, or whether 'UI Adapter' is permitted to import from 'Integration'. The two authoritative architecture documents describe structurally incompatible systems."
          },
          {
            "id": "F7",
            "severity": "major",
            "category": "context_completeness",
            "claim": "ecm:description is documented as aliasing rdfs:comment in prose but has no @context mapping. The \u00c2\u00a76.3 semantic projection retains only predicates in the \u00c2\u00a76.1 allowlist (rdfs:comment, not ecm:description), so the project description is silently stripped from every semantic export.",
            "evidence": "\u00c2\u00a76.2 (line 722): 'the project root carries both Semantic Layer fields (type, iao:isAbout, ecm:name, rdfs:comment via ecm:description)'. \u00c2\u00a75.4 (line 354) lists ecm:description as optional top-level. \u00c2\u00a75.2 @context (lines 290-318) contains no aliasing of ecm:description to rdfs:comment. \u00c2\u00a76.1 semantic predicate allowlist (line 700): 'id, type, rdfs:label, rdfs:comment' \u00e2\u20ac\u201d ecm:description is absent.",
            "impact": "Project descriptions are dropped from semantic JSON-LD, Turtle, and N-Triples exports despite being a documented Semantic Layer field. Round-trip equivalence (\u00c2\u00a76.4) holds canonically but semantic comparison silently diverges."
          },
          {
            "id": "F8",
            "severity": "major",
            "category": "context_completeness",
            "claim": "ecm:validationReports is used as a top-level project array in \u00c2\u00a75.4's normative example but is absent from the \u00c2\u00a75.2 @context (no @container: @set declaration) and from \u00c2\u00a75.3's canonical-ordering rules. NFR-012 lossless canonical round-trip is broken for any project that contains a validation report.",
            "evidence": "\u00c2\u00a75.4 example (line 380): '\"ecm:validationReports\": []' as top-level project key. \u00c2\u00a75.2 @context (lines 301-308) declares @container:@set for ecm:terms, ecm:instances, ecm:relations, ecm:literalAssertions, ecm:ontologies, ecm:layouts, ecm:snapshots, ecm:serializations \u00e2\u20ac\u201d ecm:validationReports is omitted. \u00c2\u00a75.3 rule 4 (line 332) enumerates the ordered-array keys; ecm:validationReports is not listed.",
            "impact": "JSON-LD expansion may produce a non-set value (single object instead of array) on round-trip; canonical serialization order is undefined; NFR-012 is unverifiable."
          },
          {
            "id": "F9",
            "severity": "major",
            "category": "semantic_projection",
            "claim": "The \u00c2\u00a76.1 semantic predicate allowlist omits ecm:name. The \u00c2\u00a76.3 projection therefore strips the project's human-readable name on semantic export, contradicting \u00c2\u00a76.2's enumeration of ecm:name as a Semantic Layer field of the project root.",
            "evidence": "\u00c2\u00a76.1 (line 700) allowlist: 'id, type, rdfs:label, rdfs:comment; rdfs:subClassOf, rdfs:subPropertyOf; ecm:classIris, ecm:subjectIri, ecm:predicateIri, ecm:objectIri; ecm:value, ecm:datatype, ecm:language; iao:isAbout; ecm:isSerializationOf, ecm:format, ecm:filename, ecm:contentHash, ecm:byteLength, ecm:generatedAt.' \u00c2\u00a76.2 (line 722): 'the project root carries both Semantic Layer fields (type, iao:isAbout, ecm:name, rdfs:comment via ecm:description) ...'. \u00c2\u00a75.4 (line 347) requires ecm:name.",
            "impact": "Project names are absent from semantic exports despite the spec asserting they are semantic. ZIP manifest \u00c2\u00a719 lists ecm:name as a manifest predicate; without an alias to rdfs:label, the resulting manifest is incomplete."
          },
          {
            "id": "F10",
            "severity": "major",
            "category": "kernel_contract",
            "claim": "SPEC \u00c2\u00a717 and COMPUTATION_MODEL.md \u00c2\u00a77 define disjoint error code vocabularies for the same kernel. SPEC's hard errors (MISSING_REALIST_ANCHOR, DANGLING_RELATION_SUBJECT_REF, MALFORMED_TERM, \u00e2\u20ac\u00a6) do not overlap with COMPUTATION_MODEL.md's INVALID_INPUT / INVALID_CONTEXT / MALFORMED_JSONLD / MISSING_MANDATORY_NODE. COMPUTATION_MODEL.md also mandates a provenance.rulesApplied output that is absent from every SPEC.md export contract.",
            "evidence": "SPEC \u00c2\u00a717.2 (lines 1240-1259) enumerates 16 hard error codes anchored in domain semantics. COMPUTATION_MODEL.md \u00c2\u00a77 'Error Code Taxonomy' (lines 137-142): INVALID_INPUT, INVALID_CONTEXT, MALFORMED_JSONLD, MISSING_MANDATORY_NODE \u00e2\u20ac\u201d and 'Error codes MUST be stable across versions'. COMPUTATION_MODEL.md \u00c2\u00a75 mandates Provenance{kernelVersion, rulesApplied}; SPEC \u00c2\u00a76.3, \u00c2\u00a719, and \u00c2\u00a75.4 example contain no rulesApplied field. CLAUDE.md \u00c2\u00a77 lists src/kernel/transform.ts and provenance.rulesApplied as load-bearing.",
            "impact": "Two normative documents specify mutually inconsistent kernel I/O contracts. Implementers cannot satisfy both without arbitrary reconciliation choices."
          },
          {
            "id": "F11",
            "severity": "major",
            "category": "product_alignment",
            "claim": "ROADMAP.md and SPEC.md describe different products. ROADMAP.md describes a generic JSON-LD identity-transform template ('Replace Identity Transform with Domain Logic'); SPEC.md describes a fully specified Visual RDF Modeler with VMP, canvas, ZIP packaging, FSA storage, and CCO/IAO anchoring. CLAUDE.md \u00c2\u00a75 instructs every session to plan from ROADMAP.md.",
            "evidence": "ROADMAP.md Phase 1 (line 9): 'Replace Identity Transform with Domain Logic.' Phase 2: 'Build Adapters'. Phases 3-4 unspecified beyond 'when Phase N is complete'. SPEC.md \u00c2\u00a729 enumerates six product-specific delivery phases (Core JSON-LD Engine \u00e2\u2020\u2019 Browser UI \u00e2\u2020\u2019 Ontology Import \u00e2\u2020\u2019 Export/Packaging \u00e2\u2020\u2019 Local Persistence \u00e2\u2020\u2019 Edge Canonical Bridge). CLAUDE.md \u00c2\u00a75 'Starting a Session' (line 95): '1. Read project/ROADMAP.md \u00e2\u20ac\u201d identify the current phase and active task.'",
            "impact": "Agents directed to plan from ROADMAP.md will plan a generic kernel template; product work on the Visual Modeler is ungated. The two authoritative documents specify different scopes."
          },
          {
            "id": "F12",
            "severity": "major",
            "category": "namespace_resolution",
            "claim": "The cco: prefix resolution is fragile and unverified. \u00c2\u00a75.2 declares cco: \u00e2\u2020\u2019 https://www.commoncoreontologies.org/ so cco:ont00000958 expands to https://www.commoncoreontologies.org/ont00000958. No fixture or golden file pins this expanded IRI; CCO's published IRI scheme has historically used the form https://www.commoncoreontologies.org/ont00000958 only in some releases and longer paths in others. NFR-013 byte-identicality is at risk if CCO changes its IRI structure between releases.",
            "evidence": "\u00c2\u00a75.2 @context (line 298): '\"cco\": \"https://www.commoncoreontologies.org/\"'. \u00c2\u00a75.2 prose (line 323): 'The cco: prefix resolves CCO IRIs of the form cco:ont00000958 to https://www.commoncoreontologies.org/ont00000958, which is cco:InformationContentEntity.' \u00c2\u00a75.14 Notes (line 639): 'cco:ont00000958 is cco:InformationContentEntity (verified against CCO \u00e2\u2030\u00a5 v1.7, 2024-11-03).' No golden file in tests/ or examples/ encodes the expanded form; no ADR in DECISIONS.md pins the CCO version.",
            "impact": "A CCO release that changes its base IRI structure will silently break NFR-013 across implementations. The 'verified against CCO \u00e2\u2030\u00a5 v1.7' claim has no in-repo verification."
          },
          {
            "id": "F13",
            "severity": "major",
            "category": "governance",
            "claim": "DECISIONS.md is a template placeholder. CLAUDE.md \u00c2\u00a75 mandates session-start reading of DECISIONS.md as durable cross-session memory, but the file contains only a generic ADR-001 dated '[TODAY]' titled 'Use JSON-LD Deterministic Service Template' \u00e2\u20ac\u201d not GraphWrite-specific.",
            "evidence": "DECISIONS.md (lines 10-22): ADR-001 names 'the JSON-LD Deterministic Service Template' as the adopted architecture, dated '[TODAY]', context refers to 'a service that produces deterministic, reproducible transformations'. No ADRs exist for OED-001 through OED-007 (resolved in SPEC \u00c2\u00a727), the CCO version pin, the iao: namespace decision, the 5-layer vs 3-layer reconciliation, or the v0.3 \u00e2\u2020\u2019 v0.4 reframing.",
            "impact": "Every per-decision rationale claimed in SPEC.md is undocumented in DECISIONS.md; CLAUDE.md's session-startup contract cannot be satisfied; future agents will re-derive (or re-debate) prior decisions."
          },
          {
            "id": "F14",
            "severity": "minor",
            "category": "version_qualifiers",
            "claim": "Multiple stale 'v0.3' qualifiers inside the v0.4 document. \u00c2\u00a75.3 rule 8 declares 'no fractional seconds in v0.3'; \u00c2\u00a77.5 defers domain/range 'to v0.4' while the spec is v0.4; \u00c2\u00a73.1, \u00c2\u00a73.2, \u00c2\u00a721, \u00c2\u00a722 (covered in F1) compound the problem.",
            "evidence": "\u00c2\u00a75.3 rule 8 (line 336): 'Use canonical ISO 8601 UTC timestamps (... no fractional seconds in v0.3).' \u00c2\u00a77.5 (line 781): 'A user who needs them can declare them via project-created assertions in v0.4. Documented as a known gap.' \u00c2\u00a75.5 closing (line 424): 'The ecm:determinism block is new in v0.3 and controls how creation-time IRIs and timestamps are produced.'",
            "impact": "Document is internally inconsistent about its own version identity; minor only because each instance is locally repairable."
          },
          {
            "id": "F15",
            "severity": "minor",
            "category": "context_completeness",
            "claim": "ecm:name has no @type or @language declaration in the \u00c2\u00a75.2 @context. Its expanded form (plain literal, xsd:string, or rdf:langString) is implementation-defined and may differ across compliant implementations, affecting semantic equivalence (\u00c2\u00a76.4) without affecting canonical equivalence.",
            "evidence": "\u00c2\u00a75.2 @context (lines 290-318) declares @type for ecm:classIris, ecm:subjectIri, ecm:predicateIri, ecm:objectIri, ecm:isSerializationOf, iao:isAbout, rdfs:subClassOf, rdfs:subPropertyOf \u00e2\u20ac\u201d but not for ecm:name, ecm:description, ecm:author, ecm:license, ecm:notes.",
            "impact": "Semantic JSON-LD round-trip equivalence depends on JSON-LD processor defaults that may differ; minor because canonical serialization (which fixes byte form) is unaffected."
          },
          {
            "id": "F16",
            "severity": "minor",
            "category": "normative_force",
            "claim": "SPEC.md contains no RFC 2119 conformance declaration despite pervasive use of lowercase 'must' / 'should' / 'may' in normative prose. ARCHITECTURE.md \u00c2\u00a71 and COMPUTATION_MODEL.md \u00c2\u00a71 carry the declaration; CLAUDE.md \u00c2\u00a70 carries it. SPEC.md does not.",
            "evidence": "ARCHITECTURE.md (line 9): 'The key words \"MUST\", \"MUST NOT\", ... are to be interpreted as described in RFC 2119.' COMPUTATION_MODEL.md \u00c2\u00a71 (line 5) same. CLAUDE.md preamble same. SPEC.md has no such declaration; e.g. \u00c2\u00a717.1 'Errors block save by default and block export unconditionally' (lowercase 'block') vs. \u00c2\u00a75.2 'Every project document must include this @context' (lowercase 'must').",
            "impact": "Normative force of SPEC.md statements is formally ambiguous; reviewers cannot distinguish recommendations from requirements with RFC-2119 precision."
          },
          {
            "id": "F17",
            "severity": "minor",
            "category": "tbox_resolution",
            "claim": "\u00c2\u00a75.14 declares the Project TBox 'logically present' in every project document but does not specify the byte-level relationship between the canonical project file and the TBox. The canonical serializer (\u00c2\u00a75.3) does not include TBox declarations; the semantic export (\u00c2\u00a76.3 step 5) does. Whether the TBox participates in canonical byte-identity (NFR-012, NFR-013) is undefined.",
            "evidence": "\u00c2\u00a75.14 (line 597): 'This TBox ... is logically present in every project document; it does not need to be repeated in each project.jsonld. Implementations may emit it implicitly on semantic export, or include it inline at the user's request.' \u00c2\u00a76.3 step 5 (line 732): 'Prepend the Project TBox declarations from \u00c2\u00a75.14 to the resulting RDF graph.' \u00c2\u00a75.3 (lines 327-336) makes no mention of TBox. \u00c2\u00a719 ZIP layout (line 1383): '/tbox/project-tbox.ttl' is a separate file in the ZIP, suggesting it is not part of project.jsonld.",
            "impact": "Two implementations may differ on whether a semantic JSON-LD export includes the TBox inline; byte-identicality of semantic exports under NFR-013 is unverifiable without a normative answer."
          },
          {
            "id": "F18",
            "severity": "advisory",
            "category": "unplaced_artifacts",
            "claim": "fnsr_daemon.py and state.jsonld at the repo root operate outside the documented architecture. They are not mentioned in SPEC \u00c2\u00a74.1, ARCHITECTURE.md, or any FR/NFR. state.jsonld uses https://fnsr.example/context.jsonld \u00e2\u20ac\u201d a non-resolvable example URL \u00e2\u20ac\u201d and writes wall-clock ISO-8601 timestamps into its history array.",
            "evidence": "Repo root contains fnsr_daemon.py (untracked, per git status) and state.jsonld (untracked). state.jsonld @context value 'https://fnsr.example/context.jsonld' (line 2) does not resolve. The daemon writes ts entries like '2026-05-16T07:55:43Z' into the document directly. No layer in SPEC \u00c2\u00a74.1 or ARCHITECTURE.md \u00c2\u00a74 covers this orchestrator.",
            "impact": "If fnsr_daemon.py is to be in-scope, it must be placed in the layer model and its non-deterministic timestamp generation must either be confined to an adapter or acknowledged as out-of-kernel orchestration; if out-of-scope, it should be excluded by \u00c2\u00a73.2."
          },
          {
            "id": "F19",
            "severity": "advisory",
            "category": "predicate_overload",
            "claim": "ecm:contentHash plays two roles. \u00c2\u00a75.6 ImportedOntology and \u00c2\u00a712.4 declare it 'informational only'; \u00c2\u00a75.15 Serialization makes it Required and load-bearing for the realist-anchored export manifest. The same predicate IRI is therefore both informational and load-bearing depending on the subject's rdf:type.",
            "evidence": "\u00c2\u00a75.6 (line 437): ImportedOntology field 'ecm:contentHash: \"sha256-...\"'. \u00c2\u00a712.4 (line 977): 'The ecm:contentHash of an imported ontology is informational only; it is not used as an integrity check on load.' \u00c2\u00a75.15 (line 660): 'Required: id, type, ecm:format, ecm:filename, ecm:contentHash, ecm:generatedAt, ecm:isSerializationOf.' \u00c2\u00a719 manifest (line 1399): 'one ecm:Serialization entry per artifact ... with ... SHA-256 ecm:contentHash.'",
            "impact": "Validation tooling cannot uniformly enforce ecm:contentHash semantics. Either split into two predicates (ecm:ontologyContentHash informational, ecm:serializationContentHash normative) or specify the dual role explicitly in \u00c2\u00a75.2 with subject-type-conditioned rules."
          }
        ],
        "cross_doc_conflicts": [
