            "id": "M1",
            "severity": "blocking",
            "claim": "The `iao:` @context binding `http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/iao#` cannot reach any real OBO IAO term, and the spec's TBox does not declare `iao:isAbout`. OBO IAO uses underscored, integer-suffixed term IRIs under the `http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/` PURL convention (the IAO 'is about' predicate is `http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000136`), not a hash-style namespace. Under the spec's @context, `iao:isAbout` expands to `http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/iao#isAbout` \u00e2\u20ac\u201d an IRI IAO does not publish and the spec's own TBox does not declare. F4 captures the hijacking of `iao:OntologyDesignPattern`; what F4 misses is that the same @context binding makes the realist-anchoring predicate `iao:isAbout` itself unreachable. Every realist claim (NFR-014, DoD #1 / #11, \u00c2\u00a722 MVP step 3 / step 18, \u00c2\u00a75.4 required field) rests on a property that is neither IAO's nor declared by this spec.",
            "evidence": "SPEC.md:297 `\"iao\": \"http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/iao#\"`; SPEC.md:609-635 \u00c2\u00a75.14 TBox (declares iao:OntologyDesignPattern but not iao:isAbout); SPEC.md:350,384-394 \u00c2\u00a75.4 / \u00c2\u00a75.4.1 normative use of iao:isAbout; OBO IAO publishes `is about` as `http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000136` (OBO PURL convention). Resolution requires either binding `iao:` to `http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/` and using `iao:IAO_0000136` form (and re-minting OntologyDesignPattern under ecm:), or declaring iao:isAbout explicitly in \u00c2\u00a75.14 with the understanding that it is also project-introduced \u00e2\u20ac\u201d which collapses the realist claim of 'using IAO's predicate'."
          },
          {
            "id": "M2",
            "severity": "major",
            "claim": "Canvas-layout nested arrays have no canonical ordering rule. \u00c2\u00a75.3 rule 4 specifies lexicographic id-ordering only for the eight top-level array keys (`ecm:terms`, `ecm:instances`, `ecm:relations`, `ecm:literalAssertions`, `ecm:ontologies`, `ecm:layouts`, `ecm:snapshots`, `ecm:serializations`). The `ecm:nodes` and `ecm:edges` arrays inside each `ecm:CanvasLayout` (\u00c2\u00a75.11) have neither id fields (CanvasNode keys on `ecm:instanceIri`; CanvasEdge keys on `ecm:relationId`) nor an ordering rule. Two implementations producing the same set of canvas nodes will canonicalize them in arbitrary orders, breaking NFR-012 (lossless canonical round-trip) and NFR-013 (cross-implementation byte-identity) for any project with a layout \u00e2\u20ac\u201d i.e., effectively every UI-edited project.",
            "evidence": "SPEC.md:327-336 \u00c2\u00a75.3 rule 4 enumeration; SPEC.md:530-554 \u00c2\u00a75.11 CanvasLayout / CanvasNode / CanvasEdge (no id fields, no ordering rule); SPEC.md:1421-1422 NFR-012, NFR-013."
          },
          {
            "id": "M3",
            "severity": "major",
            "claim": "The canonical form of `@type` (aliased as `type`) for single-typed entities is undefined. \u00c2\u00a75.4 line 345 mandates the project root emit `type` as a lexicographically-sorted array even though it has two values. \u00c2\u00a75.7 line 452 emits `\"type\": \"owl:Class\"` as a scalar. \u00c2\u00a75.3 specifies neither which form is canonical nor under what condition. JSON-LD compaction permits either. Two implementations canonicalizing the same logical project \u00e2\u20ac\u201d one that always emits arrays, one that collapses single-element arrays to scalars \u00e2\u20ac\u201d will produce different bytes for every term, instance, and assertion in the file. NFR-013 is unverifiable.",
            "evidence": "SPEC.md:345 \u00c2\u00a75.4 array form requirement; SPEC.md:452 \u00c2\u00a75.7 scalar example; SPEC.md:473 \u00c2\u00a75.8 scalar; SPEC.md:493 \u00c2\u00a75.9 scalar; SPEC.md:325-336 \u00c2\u00a75.3 (silent on scalar/array)."
          },
          {
            "id": "M4",
            "severity": "major",
            "claim": "Internal contradiction between \u00c2\u00a75.14 TBox and \u00c2\u00a77.5 deferral. \u00c2\u00a75.14 lines 626-629 declare `ecm:isSerializationOf` with `rdfs:domain ecm:Serialization ; rdfs:range iao:OntologyDesignPattern`. \u00c2\u00a77.5 line 780-782 states 'The MVP does not model rdfs:domain / rdfs:range as first-class TBox fields. A user who needs them can declare them via project-created assertions in v0.4. Documented as a known gap.' The spec's own normative TBox uses domain/range while declaring that domain/range is not modeled until users add them. Either \u00c2\u00a77.5 must be revised to exclude the Project TBox, or \u00c2\u00a75.14 must avoid rdfs:domain/rdfs:range \u00e2\u20ac\u201d at present, an implementer cannot tell whether to emit them.",
