          },
          {
            "id": "I8",
            "title": "Phase 1 parenthetical justifies a 'minimal Turtle parser' against a test type that does not require it, creating an unanchored deliverable with no FR reference",
            "consensus": "both_agree",
            "resolution": "merge",
            "severity": "minor",
            "rationale": "Phase 1 NOT-in-scope reads: 'Full Turtle term extraction and ontology import workflow \u00e2\u20ac\u201d Phase 3 (a minimal Turtle parser is sufficient here for emitter golden-file tests).' Emitter golden-file tests compare generated Turtle output byte-for-byte against a committed file \u00e2\u20ac\u201d they do not require a Turtle parser. The critic sharpened the argument materially: the \u00c2\u00a717.6 validity check ('Generated Turtle and N-Triples must parse cleanly under N3.js with no errors') is the use case that requires a parser, and it is explicitly Phase 4 scope in the ROADMAP ('Generated-artifact validity check: Turtle and N-Triples parse cleanly under N3.js with no errors (\u00c2\u00a717.6)'). Phase 1's parenthetical therefore justifies a Phase-1 component against a test type that doesn't need it. The result is a scoped-but-unanchored deliverable with no FR reference, no Phase-1 acceptance criterion, and an undefined relationship to Phase 3's 'full' version. The source artifact confirms both the NOT-in-scope parenthetical and the Phase 4 \u00c2\u00a717.6 scope line.",
            "trace": {
